{"_id":"0zh62PIPTp48Dxx7","name":"Arcane Background (Bard)","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Bard)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Bard)]{Arcane Background (Bard)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Bard]{Bard}</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit})</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Performance:</strong> Bards may take Edges that require Arcane Background (Magic).</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>When a skald rolls a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} roll to cast a power, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 10</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Accelerate Healing]{Accelerate Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Battle Song]{Battle Song}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fortune's Favored]{Fortune's Favored}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Historian, Musician or Spy?</h2>\n<p>Bards, skalds, troubadours, song mages, are sorcerers who work their magic through the power of motion, song, poetry, and storytelling. The art is extremely ancient and found among all races, though the dragonmarked House Phiarlan maintains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Organizations in House Phiarlan]{Entertainers and Artisans Guild}, and it has dominated the industry for centuries. The house trains and licenses performers, and maintains many of the grand stages. The finest schools of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Phiarlan]{House Phiarlan} are known as the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Organizations in House Phiarlan]{Five Demesnes}. As well as being spellcasters, bards are also storytellers and poets, able to recount epic poems and stories from memory. Some play instruments, but most simply use their voice to enthrall their audience. Their talents make them popular guests. Finding a warm place to sleep and a hot meal usually requires nothing more than a tale to entertain the host.</p>\n<p>From the ancient goblin dirge singers to the entertainers of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Phiarlan]{House Phiarlan}, many cultures embrace the bard or skald as entertainer who also serves as a historian or bearer of news, a chronicler if you will. To survive on the road, a trouper must be clever, charismatic, and versatile above all. Whether a tryst with a foe resolves by silver-tongue or adamantine blade, an adventuring bard's worth truly comes from the ability to improvise a magical talent to charm, lull, or simply assist with a nearly limitless reservoir of practical knowledge and skill. While the common trope sings of a troubadour whose magic harmonizes with some cosmic symphony, those who have traversed Khorvaire have learned that inspiration is the true magic of any bardic exhibition, regardless of the medium.</p>\n<p>Bards usually don’t end up as wandering minstrels or street performers—any expert with some training and skill can fill that role. Instead, some skalds use their magical abilities to unearth ancient lore, while others use their interpersonal skills and mystical music to advance their careers as spies, ambassadors, diplomats, and chroniclers. As such, skalds find employ as adventurers, as well as in governments and among the mercantile houses.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo} produces a large number of bards, since the gnomes’ love of knowledge makes them particularly well suited to this class. In other areas, bards appear most often in the large cities and towns throughout @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Breland]{Breland}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Karrnath]{Karrnath}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Thrane]{Thrane}, and (particularly) @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Aundair]{Aundair}. Bards with wilder ties are found in the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Eldeen Reaches]{Eldeen Reaches}, particularly among the druid sect of the Greensingers.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>Bards have a unique way of tapping into the magic that pervades Eberron: through music. Some bards claim that the Dragon Above sang the world into being at the dawn of time, and that their music is an echo of that powerful tune of creation.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings} for a skald will always manifest as something with the performing arts. Song and sonic trappings would be the most common. But other trappings could include playing an instrument, dancing, a poetic verse, and anything else of the like.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2}}}
{"_id":"10an4NUn4mkN7MDE","name":"Train","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Train</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>An adventurer can practice a specific skill or attribute to temporarily increase its effectiveness. A character might train @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} by sparring with a swordmaster, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} by public speaking, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} by studying forbidden tomes, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} or @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} with vigorous exercise, and so on.</p>\n<p>The character must possess at least d4 in any skill chosen for training. Afterwards, she gets one free reroll when failing that skill or attribute for one entire encounter. This stacks with any other rerolls she may have from other sources.</p>\n<p>The player chooses when to activate her rerolls as a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Actions]{free action}.</p>\n<p>If she Trains again, the previous focus is lost.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Downtime Activities</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carouse}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Center}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earn]{Earn}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchant]{Enchant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Train]{Train}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Research]{Research}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{Rest}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_n7jrsmqk7vn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Downtime","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"1EDKN7kS6pIry1y7","name":"Variable Glorious Deeds","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Variable Glorious Deeds</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>After each adventure, and only when the heroes return to civilization, one of the party may begin telling the tale of their epic battles and heroic deeds. The character makes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll, modified as below.</p>\n<p>The DM is always free to add positive modifiers for truly heroic actions or based on the character's weaknesses and how he overcame them. Always try to think of how the heroes' true exploits (as opposed to any extra bits they invent) sound as a tale told by skalds. This is important, as it is the listeners on Khorvaire who are effectively granting them Glory.</p>\n<p>Ideally, an extra +1 or +2 should be the maximum. For instance, slaying a dread liche is certainly worthy of praise, but that is already covered in the table. However, lopping off his head with a Called Shot as the killing blow is worth a small modifier, as it's the sort of detail found in epic poems.</p>\n<p>Likewise, a Novice party with a d6 as their highest combat skill (including arcane skills) who slay a bunch of orc warriors in melee without any assistance should be rewarded with a greater chance of fame.</p>\n<p>The DM may also opt to add penalties to reflect weaker opponents (such as unarmed or unarmored orcs) or favorable character circumstances (every hero had a dozen alchemical <em>blast</em> devices on hand).</p>\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Glorious Deeds Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Reason</th>\n<td class=\"table-column-header\" style=\"width:20%\">Modifier</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Storyteller</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Is a bard/skald/storyteller</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Has negative Glory</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Highest Character Rank</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Seasoned</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Veteran</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heroic</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Legendary</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Highest Number of Foes</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>You outnumbered them</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>They outnumbered you more than 2 to 1</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>They outnumbered you more than 4 to 1</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>They outnumbered you more than 10 to 1</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Highest Foe's Toughness</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4 or less</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5 to 6</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7 to 10</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11 to 15</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16 to 20</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>21 or more</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Wild Cards</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Per Wild Card</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Per named Wild Card</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Per Wild Card killed in a single blow</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Magic</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A foe had an AB with 5 or less powers</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A foe had an AB with 6 to 10 powers</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A foe had an AB with 11+ powers</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>The had power magical items</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>The foe had a relic</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Arcane Background:</strong> Where multiple foes with an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Background} were defeated, only the highest bonus applies.</p>\n<p><strong>Character Rank: </strong>The higher the heroes’ @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Rank}, the more dangerous foes they must overcome before anyone is interested in their tales. After all, when you’ve already slain a giant, who cares if you killed an orc chieftain?</p>\n<p><strong>Foes’ Toughness:</strong> Once you start talking about fighting a giant, listeners tend to forget or lose interest in the orcs you defeated in an earlier encounter. As such, only the highest @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness} of defeated foes counts.</p>\n<p><strong>Named Wild Card:</strong> No one really cares much if a hero slays a generic orc chieftain, but the slaying of Nargal the Terrible is a notable deed. Not every @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} should, or indeed can, be named. Sometimes a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} orc chief is just a nameless foe.</p>\n<p><strong>Number of Foes:</strong> As with foes’ @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}, once you begin telling how the party slew a dozen orcs in one encounter, talk of beating five or six tends to become dull to the average listener. As such, only record the greatest number of foes slain in a single encounter. Defeating three orcs in one room and eight in another equates to only eight orcs.</p>\n<p>The party size includes any allies on the heroes’ side—a party with 20 members must defeat a lot of foes at once to get noticed. Even if the heroes forget to mention their helpers, any survivors will be telling their own stories across Rassilon.</p>\n<p><strong>Single Blow:</strong> A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} killed in a single blow must have been unwounded when the killing blow was delivered. Chopping the head off a dread liche with 3 wounds is not exactly heroic.</p>\n<p>Likewise, the foe must have been aware of the party and capable of retaliation—slaughtering sleeping dragons or <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangled}</em> giants doesn’t make a good story, though the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> spell might be worth a small bonus.</p>\n<p><strong>Storyteller:</strong> Although anyone can tell a story, skalds are trained in using the right words and adjusting the rhythm to keep an audience enthralled. They can turn even a mundane adventure into an epic struggle.</p>\n<h3>GLORY AWARDS</h3>\n<p>With a success, every hero involved in the action gains 1d6 Glory. A raise increases this to 2d6. Failure earns no bonus or penalty. A critical failure, however, causes the loss of 1d6 Glory, perhaps because the listeners disbelieved the storyteller or doubt the prowess of the party to achieve what they claim. Roll the dice for each individual member of the party earning or losing Glory.</p>\n<p>Glory awards can be altered by the GM, but this should be done only for truly notable actions. Modifiers normally apply solely to individual members of the party, not every member.</p>\n<p>For instance, the hero who delivered the Called Shot to the head, killing the dread liche, should earn a +1 or +2 bonus for his notable deed. This actively encourages use of special maneuvers and imaginative combat, as opposed to the standard \"attack–damage\" routine.</p>\n<p>Of course, if one hero played little part in the action, perhaps because he was Incapacitated early on or spent the whole time cowering in fear, he should receive less Glory than those who were in the thick of the action. Just because he's a player character and was present does not entitle him to the same reward as those who risked their lives and took part in the bulk of the action.</p>\n<p>Such a hero may roll his dice with a –3 penalty, for example, possibly earning a small penalty overall with an unlucky roll because of his inaction.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Additional Glory Articles</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Variable Glorious Deeds]{Variable Glorious Deeds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fixed Glory Awards]{Fixed Glory Awards}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory Benefits]{Glory Benefits}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Losing Glory]{Losing Glory}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_lfqse89fhyg","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"1OqUkTn0tSLDucmw","name":"Warforged","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Warforged</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The warforged were built to fight in the Last War. While the first warforged were mindless automatons, House Cannith devoted vast resources to improving these steel soldiers. An unexpected breakthrough produced sapient soldiers, giving rise to what some have only grudgingly accepted as a new species. Warforged are made from wood and metal, but they can feel pain and emotion. Built as weapons, they must now find a purpose beyond war. A warforged can be a steadfast ally, a cold-hearted killer, or a visionary in search of meaning.</p>\n<h3>Living Steel and Stone</h3>\n<p>Warforged are formed from a blend of organic and inorganic materials. Root-like cords infused with alchemical fluids serve as their muscles, wrapped around a framework of steel, darkwood, or stone. Armored plates form a protective outer shell and reinforce joints. Warforged share a common facial design, with a hinged jaw and crystal eyes embedded beneath a reinforced brow ridge. Beyond these common elements of warforged design, the precise materials and build of a warforged vary based on the purpose for which it was designed.</p>\n<p>Although they were manufactured, warforged are living humanoids. Resting, healing magic, and the Medicine skill all provide the same benefits to warforged that they do to other humanoids. </p>\n<h3>Warforged Personality</h3>\n<p>The warforged were built to serve and to fight. For most of their existence, warforged had a clearly defined function and were encouraged to focus purely on that role. The Treaty of Thronehold gave them freedom, but many still struggle both to find a place in the post-war world and to relate to the creatures who created them.</p>\n<p>The typical warforged shows little emotion. Many warforged embrace a concrete purpose—such as protecting allies, completing a contract, or exploring a land—and embrace this task as they once did war. However, there are warforged who delight in exploring their feelings, their freedom, and their relationships with others. Most warforged have no interest in religion, but some embrace faith and mysticism, seeking higher purpose and deeper meaning.</p>\n<p>The typical warforged has a sexless body shape. Some warforged ignore the concept of gender entirely, while others adopt a gender identity.</p>\n<p>The more a warforged develops its individuality, the more likely it is to modify its body, seeking out an artificer to customize the look of its face, limbs, and plating.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Built for War:</strong> Warforged were designed, built, and trained as tools of war. Negotiations were not part of their training, and their world knowledge off of the battlefield is limited. They do not have @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} as core skills.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Composite Plating]{Composite Plating}: </strong>A warforged is covered in tough plating made of magically-treated woods and metals. Warforged gain a +2 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{Armor}. Warforged are unable to wear additional @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{armor}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Living Construct]{Living Construct}:</strong> Warforged are living constructs made from organic and inorganic matter and are capable of emotions and conscious thought. They do not need to breathe, eat, or drink, and are immune to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Disease]{disease}. Warforged also don’t need to sleep, and arcane powers can’t put them to sleep. Warforged must spend at least six hours in a relaxed state. In this state, they appear inert, but remain conscious, and they can see and hear as normal.\n<p>Wounds must be mended via the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Repair]{repair}</em> power or the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} skill. Each attempt takes one hour per current @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Wound} level and ignores the “@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Healing]{Golden Hour}”.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Outsider (Warforged)]{Outsider (Major)}: </strong>With a history of being dedicated soldiers of war, warforged have difficulty blending into post-war Khorvaire. Most non-warforged strongly dislike the sight of warforged as they stand as living reminders of the horror that was the Last War. As such, warforged have –2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{persuasion} rolls when interacting with non-warforged and are often treated with less rights that others.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Specialized Design]{Specialized Design}:</strong> Warforged are typically designed for specific purposes. They start with a d4 in any skill based on their experiences, education, training. If the chosen skill is a core skill, it starts at d6 and the skill's maximum increases to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Steel Fists]{Steel Fists}:</strong> Warforged fists are @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons} that cause @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength}+d4 damage.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/warforged.webp\" /></div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/warforged.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.yWt3PCcYjHyfqmlo"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"1moQNKxaCPWQIOj2","name":"Ranger","content":"<p>The classic image of the ranger is a warden of the wilds, a cunning skirmisher with a touch of druidic magic, but the ranger can fill many roles. A typical ranger is perceptive and stealthy, familiar with the wilds and a subject matter expert on the habits and tactics of a variety of Enemies.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Animal Handling, Fighting, Healing, Notice, Riding, Shooting, Stealth, Survival</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Ambidextrous, Fleet-Footed, Quick</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Dead Shot, Extraction, Improved Extraction, Favored Foe, Marksman, Two-Fisted</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Explorer, Monster Hunter, Woodsman</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Beast Bond, Beast Master, Healer</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.au2sH7tVPH13NkjL"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"2HGamkq36yCiPTDV","name":"Nautical Contact","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Nautical Contact</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>On a clear day, ships often spy each other at tremendous ranges. Catching a foe at such ranges and with relatively slow-moving craft can sometimes take days.</p>\n<p>If one ship is attempting to catch another, the captains make opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating} rolls. The crew can help by making a group @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Support]{Support} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating} roll. Each attempt takes about eight hours. If the pursuer wins with a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise}, the ships are engaged. If the target wins with a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise}, he has escaped. All other results mean the chase continues.</p>\n<p>Once the ships are engaged, use the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Chases and Vehicles]{Chase} system.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_500ev3usjom","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical Campaigns","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"2J8fhurXZB8yFWEu","name":"Undead Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Undead</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The taint of the grave runs through the character’s ancestry. She gains @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} to cold and increases her @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness} by +1.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>★ Advanced Form: </strong>The sorcerer is truly undead. She gains the full @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Undead]{Undead} ability and the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Outsider]{Outsider} (Major) and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Ugly]{Ugly} (Major) Hindrance. The heroine might actually be attractive but she’s still disturbing to the living!</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"2ZwhXWZQSorpBttW","name":"Cabin Fever","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Cabin Fever</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>One of the worst problems faced by a ship’s crew isn’t monsters or pirates but sheer boredom. Most of their time isn’t spent in swashbuckling adventures—it’s spent swabbing the decks, splicing ropes, or mending sails. Discipline is usually quite fierce on a boat as well. Most captains don’t allow gambling or drunkenness (it tends to cause deadly fights). That’s why sailors tend to spend so much of their hard-earned (or ill-gotten) booty in port taverns or brothels.</p>\n<p>All characters are automatically @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} after every 30 days spent at sea. The crew never becomes @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitated} due to Cabin Fever, but when that state would otherwise be met, the sailors might start whispering mutinous thoughts.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} gained through Cabin Fever can only be removed through @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carousing}.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_500ev3usjom","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical Campaigns","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"2n8Y2m5ArvGErdry","name":"Infernal Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Infernal</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>A relative made a deal with dark forces in the distant past. The character gains @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} to fire, @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Immunity]{immunity} to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison}, and adds +1 to the damage of any attack powers with a fire @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trapping}.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>★ Advanced Form: </strong>The infernal grows giant bat wings. This is a free action and grants her @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Flight]{Flight} at @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} 12.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1}}}
