{"_id":"F8WWzQRhZzNlNBjM","name":"Center","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Center</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The hero focuses on whatever brings her happiness. That might include quality time with friends, a solitary hunt through a secluded forest, riding a favorite horse, painting, reading, writing, performing, dancing, or courting a romantic interest.</p>\n<p>Whatever the activity, the goal is inner peace and happiness. Taking a week to enjoy the fruits of one’s labors grants the character @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Conviction]{Conviction}.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Downtime Activities</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carouse}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Center}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earn]{Earn}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchant]{Enchant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Train]{Train}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Research]{Research}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{Rest}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_n7jrsmqk7vn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Downtime","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"GframHMiA57wfqbr","name":"Losing Glory","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Losing Glory</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Glory can be won, bit can also be lost. In general, a hero must deliberately act in a less than heroic way to suffer a Glory penalty. Everyone makes mistakes and crosses the line at some point, but minor misdemeanors should be ignored unless the character makes a habit of such actions.</p>\n<p>Sample penalties are included below</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\" style=\"width:80%\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Glory Penalties</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Glory</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Event</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Special</td>\n<td>Slaying a good and just powerful NPC.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–1 to –10</td>\n<td>Caught committing a crime</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–3</td>\n<td>Cowardice or leaving a comrade behind</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–3</td>\n<td>Refusing orders</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–10</td>\n<td>Breaking an oath</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>NEGATIVE GLORY</h2>\n<p>Heroes with negative Glory do not earn rewards, but they do garner drawbacks.</p>\n<h3>WANTED</h3>\n<p>When a hero reaches –20 Glory, he gains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Wanted]{Wanted} (Minor) Hindrance. At –40, this changes to the Major version.</p>\n<p>Generally, the Minor Hindrance extends to a single realm, usually the one where the Glory penalty was incurred. The Major version, on the other hand, covers pretty much all the civilized, settled domains of Khorvaire. A hero who gains enough Glory to rise above the rating at which he gained this Hindrance, doesn’t lose the Hindrance. He may have performed some heroic deeds, but he is still a wanted man.</p>\n<h3>ENEMY</h3>\n<p>At –10 Glory, the hero acquires the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} (Minor) Hindrance. At –30 (or lower), the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} becomes a Major Hindrance.</p>\n<p>The exact nature of the enemy depends on the villain’s deeds. </p>\n<p>Again, it doesn’t matter if the hero’s Glory rises above the level at which he gained his foe—his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} doesn’t give up his vendetta.</p>\n<p>Should the hero gain a Major @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} while his Minor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} is still at large, the foe simply steps up his campaign against the character. Otherwise, the hero gains a new enemy.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_lfqse89fhyg","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Hn8AGLkO540uPf49","name":"Shadowing","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Shadowing</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>On occasion, a hero may wish to follow another character—a \"mark\"—without being noticed, such as following a cultist back to a hidden temple or trailing a wealthy noble. This is not the same as a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Chases and Vehicles]{Chase}—though it might lead to one if the person being followed discovers he has unwanted attention.</p>\n<p>Shadowing is an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} between the Shadower's @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth] skill @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed} by his opponent's @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice] roll. If the character is shadowing by other means of conveyance than walking, he uses the lower of his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth] or the appropriate \"maneuvering\" skill (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding], @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Piloting], etc.).</p>\n<p>Should the shadower roll at least a 4 and win the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} he manages to follow unnoticed. If his roll wins the contest but is less than a 4, the character loses his mark but isn't seen. If the hero loses the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} with a 4 or better, his target is followed but detects him. If he loses both the contest and fails to score at least a 4 on his roll, then not only does he fail to keep shadowing, but his target gets a good look at him. If the shadower is discovered, he can continue to follow his mark, but it becomes an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} of his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice] versus his opponent's @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth] (or maneuvering Trait if lower) to not lose the target.</p>\n<p>While in an urban enviroment, each roll covers roughly fifteen minutes of time, so it's possible several rolls may be required.</p>\n<p>Finally, it's very hard to shadow a target who moves faster than the follower. If the opponent has a higher base @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace}, the shadower suffers −2 to his Trait roll. If the mark's normal @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} is more than 50% higher than the follower (round up), the penalty is −4.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"cf":{"id":"temp_s3sjll7e4a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"}}}
