{"_id":"IT8HjW51sybd4iUk","name":"Magic and Powers","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Magic and Powers</h2>\n<p>Magic, and reliance upon magic, shapes and defines the societies of Eberron. For thousands of years, wizards, sorcerers, clerics, artificers, adepts, and magewrights have brought their magical talents to bear to solve the problems life poses. These solutions have helped humanoid society develop and thrive on every continent—particularly on Khorvaire. The result is a society suffused with magic. Skycoaches fly among the soaring towers of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Sharn]{Sharn}. Blacksmiths chant spells over forges to improve the way they work. Airships ferry passengers from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo} to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Karrnath]{Karrnath}. Weavers draw threads of shadow into their fabrics. Streets are illuminated with magical light, and magic marks emblazon letters of credit and other important documents. Magic is in common use by professional spellcasters, though complex difficult magic is still rare and wondrous.</p>\n<p>All races have the capability for magic, though each has its own preference for the style and kind of magic. Mundane people my not understand how magic works, but they don't fear magic and often benefit from magical technology created by the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dragonmarks]{Dragonmarked Houses} (such as <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-treasure.Everbright Lantern]{Everbright Lantern}</em> or<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-treasure.Feather Token]{Feather Tokens}</em> or witnessing the work of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Organizations in House Phiarlan]{Carnival of Shadows}).</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Magic and Powers</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Activation]{Activation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cantrips]{Cantrips}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{Schools of Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3> </h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/covers/magic-of-eberron.webp\" /></div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ogabsqlqv6a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7}}}
{"_id":"Iw2cbSmJkGTg6Bnc","name":"Brutal","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The weapon causes @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Heavy Weapon (HW)]{Heavy Weapons}.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 2</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 5,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"IwlAzxyHDWKK3dGS","name":"Gnome","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Gnome</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The average gnome has a love of knowledge that borders on obsession, a curiosity that admits no limits, and a vast collection of potentially useful information on every personal acquaintance. Most gnomes detest physical violence and prefer to solve their problems with words whether that's a bard's eloquent persuasion, a wizard's words of power, or a rogue's careful threat. They give an initial impression as friendly busybodies, always ready to lend a hand or share a story, while asking questions that tend toward the slightly-too-personal. Often, though, a cheerful and amiable gnome is methodically adding to a mental storehouse of knowledge that might one day provide important leverage.</p>\n<h3>Gnomes of Zilargo</h3>\n<p>To say that every Zil gnome is a ruthless schemer would be a hurtful exaggeration. Intrigue is the favorite pastime of most Zil, though. Every gnome child of Zilargo is taught to manipulate and deceive, and by the time they reach adulthood most have been involved in dozens of schemes and feuds, some ofwhich persist well into adulthood. Even a gnome with a good heart and noble goals-of which there are many-often still prefers to use trickery and cunning rather than the unreliable tools of honesty or brute force.</p>\n<p>Most Zil gnomes belong to the forest gnome subrace. Their natural talent for illusion aids them in trickery and entertaining, and they often use small animals as messengers and guides.</p>\n<p>When you're making a Zil gnome character, consider what kinds of schemes you or your family might be involved in. The Zil Schemes table offers some suggestions, but you should feel free to elaborate on these schemes, even to absurd extremes.</p>\n<p>Additionally, consider your relationship to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo}: why you have left, and what ties do you still have to it? Your scheme could provide a good reason for you to leave. Or you could be a sage gathering information for the Library of Korranberg or an investigator sending stories ofyour adventures back to the Korranberg Chronicle. Family is important to the Zil, and you could be pursuing your family's interests. You could even be working for the mysterious Trust, the conspiracy behind the Triumvirate's throne that quietly maintains order in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo}. Ifyou are working for the Trust, you could have a specific mission, but you could also be a sleeper agent-gathering information and allies until you're activated and you are put to your intended use.</p>\n<p><strong>Zil Names. </strong>Zil society is divided into major houses, each of which is composed of multiple families. Each gnome carries the name of a house and of a family in addition to a personal name. For example, Alina Lorridan Lyrris and Tallian Talius Lyrris are members of different families (Lorridan and Talius) within House Lyrris. Gnome names are long and lyrical; a Zil proverb claims \"the sweetest song is the name of a friend.\" Personal and clan names are usually at least three syllables long, and there is a strong tradition of alliteration.</p>\n<h3>Gnomes of the Five Nations</h3>\n<p>As they have for countless generations, insatiable curiosity and endless opportunity draw gnomes from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo} into the wider lands of Khorvaire. Most of these dispersed gnomes find new homes and integrate easily into local cultures. Gnomes can be found in any walk of life, whether they be as merchants, magewrights, scholars, or scoundrels. While the gnomes of the Five Nations aren't as inherently devious as their Zil cousins, they share the Zil emphasis on the importance of family.</p>\n<p>As a gnome character from the Five Nations, you might have a network of connections to the community your grew up in, likely built on the exchange of information. Alternatively, you might seek your own path in life, avoiding the intrigues your cousins adore.</p>\n<h3>Gnomes and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Scribing]{Mark of Scribing}</em> appears among the gnomes of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Sivis]{House Sivis}. The gnomes of this house were among the first of their kind to leave @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo} and live in human lands. They love bureaucracy and intrigue as much as the gnomes of their homeland, but they have carefully cultivated a reputation for impartiality and secrecy, since their services rely on trust.</p>\n<p>Today, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Sivis]{House Sivis} provides avenues of communication across Khorvaire. Translation, mediation, interpreting, and legal advocacy all fall within @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Sivis]{House Sivis's} broad purview, and they maintain the network of message stations that allow cross-continent communication</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Diminutive:</strong> Gnomes average only about three feet tall, reducing their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Gnome Magic]{Gnome Magic}: </strong>Gnomes are inherently magical creatures. They can cast cantrips as if they knew each of the following powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{light}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{telekinesis}</em>, and <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend}</em> using their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} (or @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} if they have one). They have 1 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Point} for activating these cantrips, regained as usual. Gnomes with an Arcane Background or Mystic Power or Dragonmark add their bonus @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Point} to their pool but must still learn the spells if they wish to cast them normally.</li>\n<li><strong>Keen Senses:</strong> Gnomes start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}:</strong> Gnomes from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Zilargo]{Zilargo} may start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Gnomish} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}:</strong> Gnome eyes amplify light. Low Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Obsessive]{Obsessive}:</strong> Gnomes start with a d4 in any one Smarts-related skill.</li>\n<li><strong>Quick Witted:</strong> Gnomes are very cunning and keen of mind. They start with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced Pace: </strong>Gnomes have short legs compared to human-sized races. Decrease their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} by 1 and their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running die} one die type.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/gnome.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/gnome.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.E6ZUzftrtdHhbmHC"},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"JA49KULZ9LXx9wnn","name":"What Are Character Concepts?","content":"<p>With all the options<span class=\"ILfuVd\"><span class=\"hgKElc\">—</span></span>between skills, attributes, and edges<span class=\"ILfuVd\"><span class=\"hgKElc\">—it can be challenging to understand how to express a character concept or idea for your character. This can be particularly difficult without character class concepts like in the oldest RPG in the world. <br /></span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"ILfuVd\"><span class=\"hgKElc\">Below are a list of a bunch of <em>possible</em> character ideas and concepts and how to build them in Savage Worlds. These are not exact builds for a particular character or concept. But these lay out the kinds of skills and edges that you might want to consider taking to build the kind of character that you are looking for. </span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"ILfuVd\"><span class=\"hgKElc\">Remember these are just <em>suggestions</em>. This is after all your character. Build the character that you are looking for that will be fun for you.</span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"ILfuVd\"><span class=\"hgKElc\">Here is something to consider with these concepts and any character in Savage Worlds since it does not have a clear path light character classes. Character classes are very clear paths for your characters to take. Since there are none, come up a clear concept and long term direction that you would like to take your character. You can even bring in character ideas from books or movies or other stories. Then look at the skills and edges and then build out a plan to create that character.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.dscZLSyEHmodbYAq"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
