{"_id":"nBdcRfjZECSXGLg8","name":"Vicious","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Melee Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>If the wielder hits with a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise}, he must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} roll or be @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Shaken}, but his damage increases by +4 (in addition to any bonus damage).</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 2</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 5,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"nN9LKNFZ9y4nHAWw","name":"Elemental Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Elemental</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The mage’s family was touched by a powerful elemental force. Choose one of the elements listed below. Your hero gains @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} to that element and one of the following abilities:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Air: </strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Flight]{Flight}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} 6.</li>\n<li><strong>Earth:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Burrow]{Burrowing} @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} 6.</li>\n<li><strong>Fire: </strong>+2 damage to damaging Powers with a fire @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trapping}.</li>\n<li><strong>Water: </strong>Enemies are automatically @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Hinder or Hurry (+1)]{Hindered} (per the modifier) when affected by your powers.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>★ Advanced Form: </strong>Once per encounter, you can unleash an elemental blast as an action. This causes 3d6 damage, uses the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{Cone Template}, and may be @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Evasion]{Evaded}.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"nQAfF0iMhrc7FkP9","name":"Arcane Background (Cleric)","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Cleric)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Cleric)]{Arcane Background (Cleric)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Cleric]{Cleric}</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit})</li>\n<li><strong>Miracles:</strong> Clerics may take Edges that require Arcane Background (Miracles).</li>\n<li><strong>Vow to Faith: </strong>Clerics have a major vow to serve their deity. Those who wish to draw energy from divine sources must uphold the principles of their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Domains]{Domain}.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>When a cleric rolls a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Domain:</strong> The Cleric must choose a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Domains]{Domain} associated with the deity or faith that they follow.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 10</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong> The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> plus all powers available from one single choosen @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Domains]{Domain}.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Divine Magic</h2>\n<p>There’s no logic to divine magic, no pure science that can explain exactly how it works. An acolyte might spend years meditating and praying, performing virtuous deeds, and tending their flock, and still never gain the power to cast a spell; meanwhile, a smith who can’t even read might feel @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onator]{Onatar’s} guiding hands and cast magecraft. Divine magic requires two things: absolute faith and a connection to a divine power source.</p>\n<p>Faith is about conviction. It can’t be something you approach rationally. You need to know in your heart that the magical effect you seek to produce with your spell should and will happen. Whether you’re smiting an enemy or healing an ally, you know that the enemy will fall and that you will save your friend. This doesn’t mean that you have to be a zealot with no doubts whatsoever; you can question your overall course of action. But you can’t think about your doubts in the moment of casting the spell; in that instant, you must have pure and absolute certainty that the spell will come to pass.</p>\n<h3>Connection to Divine Power</h3>\n<p>But faith alone isn’t enough; you also need a connection to a source of divine power. In Eberron, no one can prove whether the Sovereigns or other deities exist—if @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onatar]{Onatar} actually guides all artisans or if @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Dorn]{Dol Dorn} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} truly watch over every battlefield. But whether or not @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} exists, when her paladin smites a foe, they draw that power from something. The paladin believes it to be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} granting her favor, and maybe it is. Or maybe the shared faith of the tens of thousands of people who believe in the Sovereigns has created wells of power in the collective unconscious, and the paladin draws on this powerful force instead. In a practical sense, the truth is irrelevant; regardless of its nature and source, the power exists. And this is where science fails. The Silver Flame is a source of divine power, a force that has held demons at bay for millennia. Those who seek to defend the innocent and fight supernatural evil can draw on its power. But why does one templar become a paladin over another of equal faith? Why does an illiterate farmer gain the gift of divine magic when a religious scholar who’s spent decades studying texts doesn’t? People of faith usually respond that it’s because the farmer was chosen by Arawai, or because one templar was more open than the other to the Voice of the Flame. Maybe that’s true, or maybe it’s all just luck.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>To the outside observer, divine magic is very different in flavor from arcane magic. A wizard traces glowing sigils and speaks words in a language older than humanity; a cleric simply points dramatically at their enemy and calls on the Silver Flame to strike them down. Whether a spell is fueled by arcane or divine power, however, it still requires verbal and somatic components. Practically speaking, this means the cleric has to be able to speak and use their hands, and that these are somehow tied to casting a spell. But where a wizard may recite a complex incantation, the verbal component of divine magic could be the simplest of prayers: “@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} smite my foe!” or “Stand revealed in the light of the Flame!” Or it might be more complex, perhaps singing a hymn or reciting a passage from an ancient text. In both cases, the verbal components are statements of conviction and intent. Just as arcane magic is more than words and gestures, divine magic likewise has a mental component. The caster doesn’t just ask for something; they reach out and take the power from the divine source, and if they draw too heavily on this connection, it can backlash on them.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings} for divine magic vary greatly depending on the faith or diety of the the clergy. A follower of the  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Devourer]{Devourer} <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} </em>might be a shock of lightning while a <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} </em>from a disciple of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Silver Flame]{Silver Flame} might manifest as a silvery flame. View the specific suggestions on the various deities or faiths.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7}}}
{"_id":"nq8FwyhUkBmP9NDc","name":"Expedition Guide","content":"<p>Whether exploring the ruins of Xen’drik, or traversing the wilds across the continent of Khorvaire, an expedition guide knows his way around and can navigate the way for others. Expedition guides are often hired by professors from places like Morgrave University, or working for the Wayfinders Society. They might also be familiar with the indigenous cultures and languages to assist in the process of navigating the locals.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Notice, Persuasion, Survival</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Linguist</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Explorer, Woodsman</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Common Bond</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Danger Sense, Scavenger</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.jpRmR1FLNJcgVTqr"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"nrjDxoCofmu2fYWi","name":"Inquisitive","content":"<p>Most typically, inquisitives are members of House Medani’s Warning Guild, and sometimes members of House Tharashk. There are more than a handful that work independently, mostly because they’re just that good at what they do. Serving as private investigators and detectives for hire, inquisitives are cunning, perceptive, and resourceful.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Common Knowledge, Dragonmark Focus, Intimidation, Notice, Persuasion, Research, Taunt, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Alertness, Arcane Background (Dragonmark of Detection or Dragonmark of Finding)</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Escape Artist, Investigator</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Menacing, Streetwise</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.vHIOvewOSeq7KPfM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"oLAjTLkRfe8KA6ui","name":"Crew Pay","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Crew Pay</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The standard fee for sailors is 50 silver sovereigns per month. A crew of 12, for example, costs 600 sp each month in wages. The captain must also pay for their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{provisions}.</p>\n<p>First mates, mages, navigators, healer, artificers, and other specialized crew cost at least an additional 100 sp per month.</p>\n<p>If the crew comes upon a prize of some kind, such as a floating hulk, buried treasure, or the Booty of some creature they manage to kill, it is divided up in shares.</p>\n<h3>Shares</h3>\n<p>Pirate ships and privateers don’t pay their crews—they give them shares of any booty. Paid crews use shares as well when figuring how to split unexpected payouts.</p>\n<p>The typical arrangement often is two shares for the ship’s “bank,” (to be used for repairs, provisions, and so on), three shares for the captain, two shares for the first mate, navigator, mages, super, and surgeon. The rest of the crew get one share each.  </p>\n<h2 class=\"blue-example\">Example: The Jolly Edward's salvage</h2>\n<p><em>The Frigate Jolly Edward sets sail with twelve crew. The crew includes the captain, the first mate, an artificer, and navigator. For the ship this creates a total of 20 shares on the Jolly Edward. 2 for the ship, 3 for captian, 2 for first mate, 2 for artificer, and 9 for the rest of the crew.</em></p>\n<p><em>The Jolly Edward comes upon a derelict ship. They salvage the cargo on board it. When the cargo is finally sold at Regalport. The Jolly Edward gains 400 galifars. So each share is worth 20 galifars. The ship's \"bank\" gets 40 galifars, the captain 60, first mate and artificer 40 each, and each of the rest of the crew gets 20 gp.</em></p>\n<p><strong>Hunger:</strong> Wild Cards suffer from starvation normally (one provision a day counts as adequate food). For the rest of the crew, make a group @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} roll each day they have half rations (one provision for every two men). Subtract 2 if the men have less than this.</p>\n<p>Should the crew collectively reach @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitated} state, 10% of the men perish each day from starvation. Most crews mutiny long before this starts to happen.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_500ev3usjom","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical Campaigns","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"ofFuPTnVboV6K9vd","name":"Glamered","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Armor Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Upon command, a piece of glamered armor changes shape and appearance to assume the form of a normal piece of clothing. The armor retains all of its properties when it is so disguised.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 0</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 900 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"pIXs0JkdAj0IYDDL","name":"Distance","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Ranged Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Decrease any @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Range} penalties by one when using this weapon.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"pbCQNBzz4ARtuBAk","name":"Animated","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Shield Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Once per encounter, an animated shield can be loosed to defend its wielder. For the next three rounds, it hovers near its owner, following him if he moves and granting its @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Parry]{Parry} and cover bonus as usual without needing to be held. Its type still applies for purposes of Armor Interference or Restriction.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 3</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 10,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"qGjYjXzmRCGp041W","name":"Diplomat","content":"<p>Khorvaire is a miasma of different races and cultures, and keeping the peace of the Last War is a full time job. As well as trying to maintain the status quo, many diplomats seek to better the options for their nations with the Dragonmark Houses.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Taunt</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Femme Fatale/Ladykiller</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Reliable, Work the Room</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.loVCK5EwenityQtq"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"r1TYWhlyGeNUcC8c","name":"Downtime","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Downtime</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Adventurers often have time between their epic quests. Some might spend it practicing their sword fighting techniques or enchanting magic items. Others may pray to their gods, try to earn a few coins in town, spend time with their friends, or aid locals in need.</p>\n<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When the party has at least a week between adventures.</p>\n<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each player chooses one of the activities below and gains its benefits.</p>\n<h3>PERSONAL TIME</h3>\n<p>When the Game Master decides there’s Downtime of at least a week, you can choose one of the following activities. Each provides a benefit of some sort, from financial rewards to limited but valuable skill bonuses. Narrate what your hero is doing then follow the instructions under each activity.</p>\n<p>Unless an option says otherwise, its effect may only be gained once regardless of how long the downtime lasts.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Downtime Activities</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carouse}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Center}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earn]{Earn}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchant]{Enchant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Train]{Train}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Research]{Research}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{Rest}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":9},"cf":{"id":"temp_s3sjll7e4a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"r5lE43dA61yrLc1J","name":"Careening","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Careening</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Wooden vessels must be “careened” on occasion. The ship is beached and turned on its side so that barnacles, sea worms, and other parasites can be scraped off. Failure to careen a ship every four months decreases its speed. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Vehicle Notes]{Handling} is reduced by one every month thereafter, to a maximum penalty of –4.</p>\n<p>Any of the Great Ports offer careening for 50 golden galifars times the vessel’s base @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}, and is done in a number of days equal to half its base @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}.</p>\n<p>A ship can also be careened on an island by its crew. This is a tiring and tedious process, taking a number of days equal to the craft’s base @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness} (a base @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness} of 17 requires 17 days, for instance). This is an average number based on the standard crew for a ship that size. A crew with twice the usual number of workers can careen the vessel in half the time, half the required crew takes twice the time, and so on.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_500ev3usjom","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical Campaigns","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"rx9Hgk3J6ChBpjMP","name":"Ranged Weapons Table","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Ranged Weapons</h2>\n<div class=\"table-summary\">\n<p>All the available ranged weapons.</p>\n</div>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Range</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Damage</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">AP</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">ROF</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Min Str.</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Cost</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"8\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Common Weapons</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Axe, Throwing]{Axe, Throwing}</td>\n<td>3/6/12</td>\n<td>Str+d6</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>5 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bow]{Bow}</td>\n<td>12/24/48</td>\n<td>2d6</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>30 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bow, Long]{Bow, Long}</td>\n<td>15/30/60</td>\n<td>2d6</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d8</td>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>75 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bow]{Bow, Composite}</td>\n<td>12/24/48</td>\n<td>Str +d6</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>100 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Crossbow, Hand]{Crossbow, Hand}</td>\n<td>6/12/24</td>\n<td>2d4</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>75 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Hand-drawn.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Crossbow, Heavy]{Crossbow, Heavy}</td>\n<td>15/30/60</td>\n<td>2d8</td>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>50 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Requires a windlass to load. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Reload]{Reload} 2.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Crossbow, Light]{Crossbow, Light}</td>\n<td>10/20/40</td>\n<td>2d6</td>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Hand-drawn.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Javelin]{Javelin}</td>\n<td>3/6/12</td>\n<td>Str+d6</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>5 sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Knife]{Knife}</td>\n<td>3/6/12</td>\n<td>Str+d4</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>2 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Sling]{Sling} (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing))</td>\n<td>4/8/16</td>\n<td>Str+d4</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>1 sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"8\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Exotic Weapons</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Boomerrang, Talenta]{Boomerrang, Talenta}</td>\n<td>6/12/24</td>\n<td>Str+d4</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>15 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>On a miss, returns to the thrower.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Boomerrang, Xen'drik]{Boomerrang, Xen'drik}</td>\n<td>6/12/24</td>\n<td>Str+d4</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>20 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>On a miss, returns to the thrower.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Cutting Wheel]{Cutting Wheel}</td>\n<td>2/4/6</td>\n<td>Str+d4</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>15 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Wielder ignores the –2 penalty on @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} rolls to resist @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Disarm] attempts.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Net (Weighted)]{Net (Weighted)}</td>\n<td>3/6/12</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>1 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>A successful hit means the target is <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled}</strong>. The net is @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Breaking Things]{Hardness} 10 and vulnerable only to cutting attacks.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ib2qus6sn1","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/2.1. Gear Tables","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"sG7NzEEiEQKZAHro","name":"Arrow Deflection","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Shield Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Ranged attacks against the bearer suffer an additional −1 penalty, regardless of the attacker's position (front, rear, etc).</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"synczfLjS5SKBd3b","name":"Shields Table","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Shields</h2>\n<div class=\"table-summary\">\n<p>Shields add to a character’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Parry} as long as the defender is aware of the attack. Light shields add +1, and medium and large shields add +2. Facing in melee can usually be ignored since a defender can turn to face individual opponents throughout the combat round. If she's attacked by multiple creatures on the same <em>Action Card</em>, however, the shield protects against half the attackers (rounded up; defender's call which ones). Ignore that if the shield bearer has a superior position, such as flanked by allies with no foes behind them, blocking a doorway, corner, or narrow hallway, and so on. If using miniatures, remember that they're static but characters in the game world aren't.</p>\n<p>The Parry bonuses from a shields is written in parentheses next to a character’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Parry}, like this: 8 (2). This means 2 points of the character’s 8 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Parry} comes from a shield. Half of the foes who attack this character on the same Action Card can bypass those 2 points but not the other 6.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} subtracts from ranged attacks from the front and shielded side (attacks from the rear or unprotected side ignore cover). Unless stated otherwise, shields are @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Breaking Things]{Hardness} 10.</p>\n<p>While worn, shields can be used to bash. Buckler shields do Str damage, heater shields/round shields do Str+d4, and kite shields/tower shields do Str+d6.</p>\n</div>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Parry</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Cover</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Min Str.</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Cost</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"6\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Shields</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Buckler Shield]{Buckler Shield}</td>\n<td>+1</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>d4</td>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>5 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Heater Shield]{Heater Shield}</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>−2</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>10 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Round Shield]{Round Shield}</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>−2</td>\n<td>d6</td>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>10 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Kite Shield]{Kite Shield} (–1 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace})</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>−4</td>\n<td>d8</td>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Tower Shield]{Tower Shield} (–1 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace})</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>−4</td>\n<td>d8</td>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"5\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper\"> <span class=\"table-subheader-center-content\">Extras</span> </span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"3\">Shield spikes</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>20 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"5\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> +1 damage when attacking with the shield.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ib2qus6sn1","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/2.1. Gear Tables","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"tPlqhMAV1a5G2VQN","name":"Trade Domain","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Trade Domain</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Aspects:</strong> Merchants, trade, negotiations, contracts, coinage, wealth</li>\n<li><strong>Deities:</strong> Kol Korran, The Keeper</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fortune's Favored]{Fortune's Favored}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{Sanctuary}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0bt6afhtf6wi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Domains","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"tRQ7DEVQtsBO0YVq","name":"Eneko","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Eneko</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The Eneko of Skyarn are distant descendants of ogres and half-giants. As refugees of the Sundering and subsequent expansion of Riedra, the eneko have now been forced into one of the last free corners of Sarlona. Also known as \"mongrel ogres\", eneko are a true breeding race in their own right with a long and rich cultural heritage.</p>\n<h3>Free People</h3>\n<p>The home of the eneko, Syrkarn, is a sanctuary of freedom, diversity and humility built out of yuan-ti ruins by refugees fleeing the monolithic culture and military of Riedra. Eneko and humans equally make up the vast majority of the loose nation's inhabitants, and the philosophy of the eneko is difficult to separate from the region they call home. Eneko from Syrkarn value community, personal freedom, and honest labour above all.</p>\n<p>Many eneko live in nomadic tribes, and those that make a home in Sykrarn's cities still must contend with the harsh storms of Sarlona and the dangerous ruins left by ancient civilizations. This trains into all eneko a profound respect for the land and its challenges, and hones their almost supernatural resilience to the elements. Eneko travelers are among the most difficult for Riedra's Thousand Eyes to track.</p>\n<h3>Mixed Bloodlines</h3>\n<p>Eneko originated from the pairings of the ogres of Borunan and the nomadic half-giants that wander the continent. According to half-giant legend, their people are the progeny of Sarlona's native humans and giant explorers from Xen'drik. Grandiose eneko may claim that the blood of the ancient human sorcerer kings and the mightiest titans of Xen'drik flows through their veins. While many Riedrans deride the eneko, labelling them \"mongrels\", eneko themselves view the diversity of their heritage as one of their greatest strengths.</p>\n<h3>Dark Magic</h3>\n<p>The arcane power displayed by their legendary forebearers leads many eneko to the study of magic. The cult of Karrak the Final Guardian, a deity sometimes called an aspect of the Keeper, is said to have its origins in the giants of Xen'drik. Riedrans and less trusting Syrk humans claim the cult of Karrak is a convenient front for the practice of dark magic.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Brute Strength:</strong> Eneko are natural strong. They start with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Clumsy]{Clumsy}: </strong>Eneko are big and clumsy. They suffer a −1 penalty to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Eneko Resilience]{Eneko Resilience}:</strong> Eneko are hardy and resistant to toxins. They gain a +4 bonus to resist the effects of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison}. Damage from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison} is also reduced by 4.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Eneko start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Riedran} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}</strong>:</strong> Eneko have the vision of their ogre ancestors. LLow Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Outsider (Eneko)]{Outsider (Minor)}:</strong> Most races are frightened by the mixed heritage of eneko, and eneko are rather reserved and wary. They have −2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} as other races tend to distrust them.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} +1:</strong> Eneko are much larger than humans, standing about 6 ½ − 8 feet tall, increasing thier @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1, combined with Brute Strength this increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} to d12+2.</li>\n<li><strong>Sturdy:</strong> Eneko have a rugged physiology. They start with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/eneko.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/eneko.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.TZdKP8aYcLMkOx4g"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"uBTm7pX6iZQK462z","name":"Earn","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Earn</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The hero earns currency in some way. Perhaps he takes on odd jobs, kills rats in the local tavern, or even \"procures\" it from the local thieves' guild!</p>\n<p>The hero must make a relevant skill roll to earn her reward—@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} for scoundrels, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} for Mercenaries, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} for entertainers, etc. Use an appropriate attribute for more mundane jobs.</p>\n<p>A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} means the character doesn't make any money and embarrasses herself somehow. If the job was dangerous, she also takes d4 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds}. Failure means she doesn't make any money and takes @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} (page 153).</p>\n<p>Success earns her 100 gp if she's @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice} rank, 200 gp if @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Seasoned}, 300 gp if @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Veteran}, 400 gp for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Heroic}, and 500 gp if she’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Legendary}. Double the reward with a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise}.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Downtime Activities</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carouse}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Center}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earn]{Earn}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchant]{Enchant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Train]{Train}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Research]{Research}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{Rest}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_n7jrsmqk7vn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Downtime","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"uHQdzY3vE0C0kcWa","name":"Random Traps","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Random Traps</h2>\n<p>Draw two cards from the Action Deck whenever you need a trap on the fly. These tell you everything you need to know about its concealment, complexity, type, and lethality. Very occasionally you'll need to draw a third card, but the rules below tell you when to do this.</p>\n<p>The GM should add suitable flavor to these draws based on the trap type. For instance, a \"blade trap\" could be a scything blade slicing from the wall at knee height or a spear which thrusts out from a concealed hole. A Spade result on the trap might indicate multiple blades, hence the high Fighting die and increased damage. A portcullis of the Club suit might be heavily corroded or made of wood, whereas a Spade indicates extremely tough and well-made bars.</p>\n<h3>First Card</h3>\n<p>The first card determines how difficult the trap is to detect and disarm. This is shown on the <strong>Trap Difficulty Table</strong> below as modifiers to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery] rolls.</p>\n<p>Note that <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{glyph}</em> traps cannot be disarmed by mundane means (and so ignore the suit), but they can be <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispelled} </em>and negated. Use the suit entry of the second card on the Trap Type table below to determine the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill} die for this purpose.</p>\n<p><strong>Detecting: </strong>Detecting a trap requires a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll. Unless a character has @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Danger Sense], searching for traps requires an action. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running} hero rolls at –2. A single roll is made in a round, regardless of how far the hero moves. With success, he detects the first trap adjacent to him. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise} locates a second trap within line of sight, if such exists. The hero may halt his movement if he spots a trap (advisable if it's right in front of him).</p>\n<p><strong>Disarming: </strong>Disarming a detected trap requires a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery] roll and takes a complete round (no other actions possible, including movement). On a critical failure, the trap activates and automatically affects the unfortunate hero.</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Trap Difficulty Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Value</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Detect</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Suit</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Disarm</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Joker</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>Joker</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2–4</td>\n<td>+1</td>\n<td>Club</td>\n<td>+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5–10</td>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>Diamond</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jack–Queen</td>\n<td>–1</td>\n<td>Heart</td>\n<td>–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>King–Ace</td>\n<td>–2</td>\n<td>Spade</td>\n<td>–2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2> </h2>\n<h3>Second Card</h3>\n<p>The second card determines the exact type of trap encountered. This is detailed on the <strong>Trap Type Table</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Wild Die: </strong>On a Joker the trap is exceptionally lethal and has a Wild Die. Draw a third card to determine the trap type. The suit of the new card indicates the Wild Die, as well as other details. Traps with a Wild Die apply it to rolls to all Trait rolls, when applicable.</p>\n<p><strong>Area: </strong>Traps usually affect a 1\" square on the battle grid. Ranged attacks use the standard range brackets for the type of missile launched. Whatever projectile is launched, range is calculated as normal. The distance listed for pits is their depth. <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph} </em>traps affect an area or operate at range as per the spell description and the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill} die.</p>\n<p><strong>Duration: </strong>Traps are generally one-shot devices. Once activated, they must be reset in order to work again. Portcullises remain in place until lifted up.</p>\n<p><strong>Initiative:</strong> Most traps activate with little warning to the unfortunate victim. Outside of combat use the rules for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Surprise]. In combat, traps being on Hold and roll to interrupt. Traps have @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} d10 for this purpose. A trap also has @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.The Drop]{the Drop} where applicable. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to avoid @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Surprise] and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} rolls to avoid interruption use the same modifier as for Detecting traps (see above).</p>\n<p><strong>Attacks: </strong>Traps which make attack rolls cannot use any combat maneuvers—they simply roll their attack die.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes: </strong>The following short codes are used on the table. Arcane = @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill}. Used when a spell activates, requires an attribute die value for any reason, and to resist dispel attempts. Fight = @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting] skill. Sh = @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting] skill (range and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} modifiers apply). @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength}–X = penalty to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} roll to lift obstacle. XdY = number and type of damage dice. #X = number of attacks a trap makes against a single victim or can split among multiple victims (GM's call based on placement). Traps which use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting] do not suffer penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}.</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Trap Type Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Value</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Clubs</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Diamonds</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Hearts</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Spades</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Joker*</td>\n<td>–</td>\n<td>d4 Wild Die</td>\n<td>d6 Wild Die</td>\n<td>d8 Wild Die</td>\n<td>d10 Wild Die</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>Portcullis**</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> –1</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> –2</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> –4</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> –6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3–4</td>\n<td>Pit Trap***</td>\n<td>10', 1d6</td>\n<td>20', 2d6</td>\n<td>30', 3d6</td>\n<td>40', 4d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Spiked Pit</td>\n<td>10', 1d6+2</td>\n<td>20', 2d6+4</td>\n<td>30', 3d6+6</td>\n<td>40', 4d6+8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6–8</td>\n<td>Projectile</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d6, 2d6, #1</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d8, 2d6, #1</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d10, 2d6, #3</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d12, 2d6, #4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9–10</td>\n<td>Blade</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d6, 2d6</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d8, 2d8</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d10, 2d10</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d12, 2d12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jack</td>\n<td>Poisoned</td>\n<td colspan=\"4\">Treat as a Projectile of the same suit. Anyone <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Shaken</a> or <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> wounded</a> must make a <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Vigor</a> roll. Roll a d10 once with failure. A 1–3 means all victims suffer a level of <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"uQyy7EfJkaHAwXMp\"> Fatigue</a> for 2d6 hours, on a 4–7 they are paralyzed for 2d6 minutes, and on 8–10 they suffer an automatic <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Wound</a>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Queen</td>\n<td>Poisoned</td>\n<td colspan=\"4\">Treat as a Blade of the same suit. Anyone <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Shaken</a> or <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> wounded</a> must make a <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Vigor</a> roll. Roll a d10 once with failure. A 1–3 means all victims suffer a level of <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"uQyy7EfJkaHAwXMp\"> Fatigue</a> for 2d6 hours, on a 4–7 they are paralyzed for 2d6 minutes, and on 8–10 they suffer an automatic <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Wound</a>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>King</td>\n<td>Falling Block</td>\n<td>2d6</td>\n<td>2d8</td>\n<td>3d6</td>\n<td>3d8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ace</td>\n<td><em><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers\" data-id=\"BTDWriPb4tGpCIQm\"> Glyph</a>****</em></td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d6</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d8</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d10</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d12</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>* Draw a third card to determine Wild Die and trap type. A second Joker indicates the trap is faulty and does not work.</p>\n<p>** Portcullis traps either have a single gate (usually to block the way the party has come and so force them forward) or drop two gates (one ahead and one behind the intruders to trap them in a small area). Due to the confines of most corridors or doorways, a maximum of two people can combine their Strength in a Cooperative roll to lift a portcullis.</p>\n<p>*** Alternately, a pit may drop the victims into a lower level of the “dungeon” rather than a small hole, thus separating the party. Another version could be a chute, which drops the victim into a cell or monster’s lair on a lower level but without inflicting any damage.</p>\n<p>**** One spell of the GM’s choice.</p>\n<h2 class=\"blue-example\">Example: Random Trap Encountered</h2>\n<p>Aelric Olafsunu is exploring a ruined temple when the GM decides to place a trap in his path. The GM draws two cards. He gets a 3 of Hearts and the King of Diamonds.</p>\n<p>The 3H tells the GM that there is a +1 bonus to the Notice roll to spot the trap (indicated by the 3) and a –1 modifier to disarm it (indicated by the Hearts). The trap is fairly complex, but not very well disguised. Unfortunately, Aelric isn't looking out for traps and walks straight onto it. The GM decides it is a pressure plate mechanism.</p>\n<p>As this occurs outside of combat, Aelric rolls his Notice to avoid Surprise. He adds +1 from the first card's value, and scores 8. The GM tells Aelric he hears an audible click as his foot hits the floor and deals him an action card. Aelric declares he wants to move clear of the square he is on. Before he can do this, however, the trap tries to interrupt him.</p>\n<p>The trap has a fixed d10 Agility and rolls a 9. Aelric rolls his Agility and gets a lousy 5. Aelric has been hit by a falling lump of masonry (as determined by the King value of the second card). He suffers 2d8 damage (determined by the Diamonds).</p>\n<p>Note that although the trap scored a raise over Aelric's Agility total, this was not an attack roll and so it does not deal +1d6 damage.</p>\n<p>Aelric suffers 11 damage, enough to cause him a wound. He vows to be more careful as he descends deeper into the temple.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":10},"cf":{"id":"temp_5qurmfm60sv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"uHeaSJHTadMAX8jK","name":"Bloodlines","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"header\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p>Bloodlines</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Below are the bloodlines available to sorcerers. Many grant various forms of @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance}.</p>\n<h2>Bloodlines</h2>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aberrant Bloodline]{Aberrant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Abyssal Bloodline]{Abyssal}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Bloodline]{Arcane}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Celestial Bloodline]{Celestial}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Destined Bloodline]{Destined}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Draconic Bloodline]{Draconic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Elemental Bloodline]{Elemental}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fey Bloodline]{Fey}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Infernal Bloodline]{Infernal}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Undead Bloodline]{Undead}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1}}}
{"_id":"uJT85p2YXMks7190","name":"Carouse","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Carouse</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Carousing characters spend their time socializing with friends, making new ones, or cementing relationships with their contacts. This usually involves considerable cost and time spent at local restaurants and taverns.</p>\n<p>During her Downtime, the character spends 50gp in food, drink, and entertainment. Double that for each @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Rank} thereafter: 100 gp for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Seasoned}, 200 gp for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Veteran}, 400 gp for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Heroic}, and 800 gp if she’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Legendary}).</p>\n<p>In exchange, she gains a local favor she can call in at any time. The greater her @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Rank} and her overall standing in the community (GM’s call), the greater the favor.</p>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/ambience/taverns/tavern-welcome-01.webp\" /></div>\n<h3> </h3>\n<h3>Carousing from Cabin Fever</h3>\n<p>A night spent carousing “resets” the crew’s clock. Start the 30-day countdown again.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} lost to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever} can only be relieved by rest and relaxation. This means carousing in a port with plenty of booze and women for most. Historically, sailors have often spent the equivalent of a year’s pay in a single week.</p>\n<p>Each week spent in port where the crew can relax (which usually means boozing and wenching) removes one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} due to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}. Each night of carousing costs [[/r 1d6*4]] gp for player characters. Extras spend their own pay or shares and their expenses should not be tracked.</p>\n<p>Caurousing in this way, <em>does not</em> gain a local favor.</p>\n<p><strong>Rushing:</strong> Characters may unwind quicker by spending more money on good food, drink, and company. Spending [[/r 2d6*4]] gp reduces the time to remove @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} to four days; [[/r 3d6*4]] gp reduces the interval to three days, and so on, to a minimum of one day and [[/r 4d6*4]] gp.</p>\n<p>Player characters can also encourage their crews along. Each additional 2 golden galifars reduces the time to remove @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} by one day, to a minimum of one day and 8 gp per head.</p>\n<p><strong>Getting Drunk:</strong> Carousing characters must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} roll each night to avoid getting drunk. A failure means they barely manage to make it back to their hammock that night, and suffer a grueling hangover the next morning (they are @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} until sometime after lunch).</p>\n<p>Success means the party-goer is drunk, but can mostly handle himself. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts}, and all related skill rolls suffer a –1 penalty, but @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness} is increased by 1.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Downtime Activities</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carouse}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Center}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earn]{Earn}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchant]{Enchant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Train]{Train}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Research]{Research}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{Rest}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_n7jrsmqk7vn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Downtime","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"uKtSQFIhQywIX0Vb","name":"Skills","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Skills</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.More Skill Points]{More Skill Points} Setting Rule is in effect, therefore all characters start with 15 points to buy skills during character creation. A skill that’s below the linked attribute (noted in parentheses beside the skill name) is cheaper to increase than one that’s at or above it. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{Character Creation}</strong> and <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Advancement}.</strong></p>\n<p>Core skills are marked with a <span class=\"red-text\">red star</span>, and start at d4 for@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{player characters}.</p>\n<p>Characters can attempt skills they don’t have but it’s more difficult. See<strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Unskilled Attempts}</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Skill changes in Savage Eberron from Savage Worlds</h3>\n<p>The following skills from <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> are <strong>not </strong>available in <cite>Savage Eberron.</cite></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Academics</span> has been renamed to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Lore]{Lore}</li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Driving</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Electronics</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Hacking</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Occult</span> has been renamed to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana}</li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Piloting</span> has been updated to be used with elemental bound vehicles.</li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Research</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Repair</span> has been updated to be used with artifice and warforged.</li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Taunt</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Skill added to Savage Eberron</h3>\n<p>The following skills from have been a added to <cite>Savage Eberron.</cite></p>\n<p><span class=\"red-text\">Animal Handling</span>, <span class=\"red-text\">Cosmology</span>, <span class=\"red-text\">Deception</span>, <span class=\"red-text\">Religion</span>, <span class=\"red-text\">Trade</span></p>\n<figure class=\"figure table-figure\">\n<figcaption class=\"figure-heading\">Skill Summaries</figcaption>\n<table class=\"table summary-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Skills</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Animal Handling]{Animal Handling} (Spirit):</span> Skill with handling and training animals.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge about the spells, artifacts, magical traditions, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (Agility):</span> Overall athletic coordination and ability. Climbing, jumping, balancing, wrestling, skiing, swimming, throwing, or catching.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle} (Smarts):</span> Strategy, tactics, and understanding military operations. A key skill in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Mass Battles]{Mass Battles}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating} (Agility):</span> Ability to sail or pilot a boat, ship, or other watercraft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} (Smarts):</span> General knowledge of a the world.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Cosmology]{Cosmology} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of the planes, their properties, inhabitants, and manifest zones.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Deception]{Deception} (Spirit):</span> The ability to convincingly hide the truth, either verbally or through actions.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} (Spirit):</span> The arcane skill for multiple arcane backgrounds.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} (Agility):</span> Skill in armed and unarmed combat.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Focus]{Focus} (Spirit):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)]{Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Gambling]{Gambling} (Smarts):</span> Skill and familiarity with games of chance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} (Smarts):</span> The ability to treat and heal @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds} and diseases, and decipher forensic evidence.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} (Spirit):</span> A character’s ability to threaten others into doing what she wants.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge and fluency in a particular @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Language}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Lore]{Lore} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of history, the Ages, legends, literature, archaeology, song, poetry, and similar fields.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} (Smarts):</span> General awareness and perception.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} (Spirit):</span> Singing, dancing, acting, or other forms of public expression. Additionally, the arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Bard)]{Arcane Background (Bard)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} (Spirit):</span> The ability to convince others to do what you want.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Piloting]{Piloting} (Agility):</span> Skill with maneuvering elemental bound vehicles.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Psionics]{Psionics} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Psionics)]{Arcane Background (Psionics)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Religion]{Religion} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge about religions, rites, traditions and symbols.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} (Smarts):</span> The ability to craft and fix mechanical gadgets, vehicles and warforged. additionally, the arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Artificer)]{Arcane Background (Artificer)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} (Agility):</span> A character’s skill in mounting, controlling, and riding a tamed beast.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Science]{Science} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of scientific fields such as biology, chemistry, geology, engineering, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} (Agility):</span> Precision with any type of ranged weapon.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for multiple arcane backgrounds.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} (Agility):</span> The ability to sneak and hide.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} (Smarts):</span> How to find food, water, or shelter, and tracking.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} (Agility):</span> Sleight of hand, pickpocketing, lockpicking, and other typically shady feats.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Trade]{Trade} (Smarts):</span> Trade let's an entrepreneur raise funds through the day-to-day running of a business.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":5}}}
{"_id":"vN3rOFTvBYis1Ybj","name":"Glory and Infamy","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"header\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p>Glory and Infamy</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<section class=\"ridged-block-float\">\n<h3>PLAYING A VILLAIN</h3>\n<p>Not every player is going to want to play a hero, and that's fine. After all, we've given the stat blocks for several evil deities, and there's no restriction on characters worshipping them. However, there is a price to pay for villainy.</p>\n<p>Heroes who perform heroic deeds earn bonuses through their elevated Glory—villains get very little reward for being evil. Of course, to earn Glory a hero has to take great risks and maintain a certain code of conduct, whereas a villain doesn't have that restriction.</p>\n<p>As such, villains are easy to play, but heroes get all the rewards for being \"forced\" to act in a certain manner.</p>\n</section>\n<p>Everything living eventually dies. However, while a mortal's flesh may rot off the bone, his name can live forever through his deeds. Skalds and bards sing tales of heroes who perished long ago, keeping the memory of these figures as alive today as it was when they walked Eberron.</p>\n<p>Glory has nothing to do with social standing, wealth, or who one calls friend—it is a mark of a character's reputation as a hero. A king may be well known across the lands, but that does not make him a hero, nor does it entitle him to become the focus of ballads or epic poems. Only through heroic deeds can a character aspire to enter the history books and oral myths of Rassilon.</p>\n<p>Your hero's Glory starts at zero, but can be affected by his or her actions during the course of the game. The higher your hero's Glory, the more renowned he is across Rassilon and the more benefits he gains.</p>\n<p>Just as Glory define the acts of a hero, so does Infamy define the acts of a villian. Infamy is Glory that has gone into the \"negative\".</p>\n<h3>Glory vs. Rank</h3>\n<p>A hero's Rank is a measure of his experience, although it does incorporate a degree of glory. Rank is a by-product of earning experience in adventures and quests, which aren't always linked to heroic deeds. Sure, the hero may rescue a princess, but the rescue might be fairly mundane and quickly forgotten. Only deeds which attract attention count toward Glory. </p>\n<h2>Gaining Glory</h2>\n<p>Glory is measured in Glory Points. Characters can rise to become famous heroes or slip into mediocrity or do deeds so heinous that they are remembered in Infamy.</p>\n<p>Glory should not be dolled out like candy. It should be earned through heroic endeavors, good roleplaying, and investing heavily in character, not expected just because the hero is a player character.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Additional Glory Articles</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Variable Glorious Deeds]{Variable Glorious Deeds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fixed Glory Awards]{Fixed Glory Awards}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory Benefits]{Glory Benefits}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Losing Glory]{Losing Glory}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7},"cf":{"id":"temp_lfqse89fhyg","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"vVXTXDS2kIVprTCL","name":"Half-elf","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Half-elf</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>From the Towering Woods of the Eldeen Reaches to the slums of Sham, half-elves are found across Khorvaire. New half-elves are born in every generation from pairings between humans, elves, and other half-elves, with children typically clinging to a parent's culture. Over centuries, though, half-elves have developed their own communities and traditions, giving them an identity strengthened by the rise of House Lyrandar and House Medani. Members of these communities generally dislike the term \"half-elf,\" instead calling themselves Khoravar, an Elvish term meaning \"children of Khorvaire.\"</p>\n<p>The elves of Aerenal have never allowed a half-elf into the Undying Court, and the Valenar elves don't consider half-elves capable of channeling a Valenar ancestral spirit. Among humans, though, half-elves don't experience any more prejudice or bias than members of other races, and some half-elves could easily be mistaken for human.</p>\n<p>In making a half-elf character, consider whether you were born in a Khoravar community, or if your parents were members of different races. Is your half-elf identity a source of pride, a simple fact of life, or something that has been difficult for you?</p>\n<h3>Khorvar</h3>\n<p>The culture that has developed among Khorvaire's native half-elves places a strong emphasis on hospitality toward other Khoravar. They don't expect each other to put themselves in danger for strangers' sake, but when possible, half-elves do what they can to help others with information, shelter, and the like. Khoravar communities have weekly unity dinners where local news and events are shared; these meals are a great chance to hear about local events and opportunities.</p>\n<p>Many Khoravar espouse the idea of \"the bridge between,\" the notion that the Khoravar are called to facilitate communication and cooperation between members of different cultures or species. Khoravar who follow this philosophy often become bards, diplomats, mediators, or translators. Others are fascinated by their distant connection to the fey and seek to build bridges between the Material Plane and the Feywild of Thelanis. These Khoravar often become Greensinger druids or warlocks with Archfey patrons.</p>\n<p>Khoravar speak both Common and Elvish, and among themselves they often blend these two together. This pidgin makes perfect sense to anyone who speaks both languages, but someone who speaks only one of them will miss some words and subtlety of meaning.</p>\n<p>As you create a Khoravar character, you have a wide range of options to describe your backstory. The Khoravar Origin table can provide inspiration for it.</p>\n<h3>Half-evles and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>Two dragonmarks appear among half-elf families: the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Detection]{Mark of Detection} </em>is found in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Medani]{House Medani} and the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Storm]{Mark of Storm} </em>in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Lyrandar]{House Lyrandar}. Both houses were established families among the Khoravar by the time their dragonmarks appeared, and they remain pillars of the Khoravar's diverse culture. The Khoravar ideal of building bridges supports the work of both houses.</p>\n<p>With the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Storm]{Mark of Storm} </em>, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Lyrandar]{House Lyrandar}. operates sailing ships and flying vessels, as well as bringing rain to farmlands. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Medani]{House Medani} uses the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Detection]{Mark of Detection}</em> to offer services of personal protection.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Elven Ancestry]{Elven Ancestry}:</strong> Half-elves retain their elven ancestral connection to arcane energies. Half-elves get a free reroll when rolling to resist enemy powers.</li>\n<li><strong>Human Adaptability:</strong> Half-elves retain the adaptability of their human ancestry. They start with a d6 in any one @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Attribute} instead of a d4. This does <em>not</em> increase the attribute limit.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}:</strong> Half-elves have the eyes of their elven ancestors and their eyes amplify light like a cat's, allowing them to see in the dark. Low Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/half-elf.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/half-elf.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.FRquWp9XZYIVKyuI"},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"vft7nES1Vn9hlMUW","name":"Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)]{Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice}, </li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill: </strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Focus]{Focus} (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit})</li>\n<li><strong>Twisted Marks:</strong> Aberrant dragonmarks often have differnt effects on the bearer. Roll on the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore-tables.Aberrant Dragonmark Flaws]{Aberrant Dragonmark Flaws} table.</li>\n<li><strong>Birthed in Tragedy: </strong>Children of Khyber are often birthed in tragedy. Roll on the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore-tables.Aberrant Dragonmark Tragedy]{Aberrant Dragonmark Tragedy} table for ideas on a tragedy you experienced.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Focus]{Focus} roll causes the aberrant a level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and all currently active powers are terminated.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>2</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 15</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{Drain Power Points}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>The Danger of Aberrant Marks</h2>\n<p>The twelve dragonmarks are tied to specific bloodlines and passed down through families. They are reliable and predictable, and their powers are constructive. They create; they heal; they protect.</p>\n<p>But there is another kind of dragonmark: marks that are unpredictable and dangerous to both the bearer and the people around them. Someone with such a mark can kill with a touch or control minds with a glance. Aberrant marks often apopear when people from different dragonmarked families produce a child, and for this reason such unions are absolutely forbidden by the Twelve. But aberrant dragonmarks can appear on members of any race, at any age, regardless of bloodline. No two aberrant dragonmarks are exactly alike—even if they grant the same power, they may appear and manifest in different ways. If two aberrant marks might grant <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>, one mark may be formed from scar tissue while another is traced on the skin in lines of cold fire.</p>\n<p>While aberrant dragonmarks can be disturbing, on the surface an aberrant mark seems no more dangerous or threatening than the powers of a sorcerer. So, what makes them significant? First of all, aberrant marks always have flaws. These may not actively hurt a character, but they are always a burden in some way—a burden that could drive a weak-willed person to madness.</p>\n<p>It takes time for a character to learn to control their mark, and in time people may be hurt. If an aberrant mark grants <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>, the person who carries it might have severely burned or even killed a loved one. Imagine having the power to cast charm person but being unable to control it and having people you care about suddenly becoming slavishly devoted to you. All of these factors have led to the general superstition that people with aberrant dragonmarks are dangerous, that their marks drive them crazy or turn them into sociopaths. These are things that can happen; people have a right to be afraid. But it is possible for an aberrant to learn to control their mark and to endure the flaw.</p>\n<h3>War of the Mark</h3>\n<p>An aberrant dragonmark is a gift of mystical power, though it can be a painful and distressing curse to bear, and its powers might even be difficult or, in some cases, impossible to control. Even an ability that duplicates a spell as simple as fire bolt can be devastating to the individual, and a person who possesses such a mark could have killed friends or even destroyed city blocks in a fiery blaze before mastering this power. This has led the common people to fear those who carry aberrant marks, paranoid that all of them could be murderers, mad, or both. The progenitor dragon Khyber is said to be the source of all things monstrous and evil, and those who carry aberrant dragonmarks in adolescence are called Children of Khyber.</p>\n<p>Aberrant marks are feared for another reason, too. Long ago, aberrant marks were more common and some held great powers. Aberrant leader Halas Tarkanan could devastate cities with powerful earthquakes. The Lady of the Plague wielded disease and commanded hordes of vermin. The dragonmarked houses united in an inquisition called the War of the Mark. Some say this was a persecution of innocents, but most feared the aberrants and stood by as the houses hunted them down. Following the War of the Mark, aberrant dragonmarks were few in number and relatively weak. But since the Mourning, aberrant marks have been appearing in greater numbers.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>Dragonmarked heirs just need to concentrate on their dragonmark to activate the powers of their dragonmark. They do not need their hands free or speak.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>All trappings of the powers from aberrant dragonmarks should reflect the general destructive and often painful qualities of the dragonmark.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":3}}}
{"_id":"vnocgzpqh1qyjkUf","name":"Tempest Domain","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Tempest Domain</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Aspects:</strong> Nautical travel, storms, weather, thunder, lightning, water</li>\n<li><strong>Deities:</strong> The Devourer</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{Drain Power Points}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-