{"_id":"wTq3kIGPky0mCbsP","name":"Character Creation Summary","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"character-creation\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Character Creation Summary</h1>\n</div>\n<h3>Concept</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Start with a general idea of what you want to play. Your setting book likely provides many ideas.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Races]{Race}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Choose your character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Races]{race} and apply any bonuses or special abilities it grants.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Select up to four points of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances} (Major Hindrances are worth 2, Minor are worth 1).</li>\n<li>For 2 Hindrance points you can raise an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{attribute} one die type, or choose an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{edge}.</li>\n<li>For 1 Hindrance point you can gain another skill point, or gain additional starting funds equal to twice your setting’s starting amount.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Attributes}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Attributes start at d4. You have 5 points to distribute among them. Each step costs 1 point.</li>\n<li>Attributes may not be raised beyond d12 unless your hero’s racial bonus states otherwise.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Skills]{Skills}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} are core skills and start at d4 for free.</li>\n<li>You have 15 points to put into these or any other skills.</li>\n<li>Each die type costs 1 point up to and equal to the linked attribute; then 2 points per step after that.</li>\n<li>Your character knows @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common} plus a number of starting @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Languages} equal to half your character’s Smarts die type. A Smarts of d6, for example, gives you three additional starting  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{languages}. </li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Derived Statistics}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Standard @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace}</strong> is 6″, but may be changed by racial abilities, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Parry}</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Vigor}, plus any @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{Armor}.</p>\n<p>Note the amount of armor in parentheses like this—Toughness: 11 (2). This means 2 points of the total 11 Toughness comes from Armor. An @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{Armor Piercing (AP)} attack could bypass those 2 points but not the other 9.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Setting Edges}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Every character starts with one free @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Class Edge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Background Edge} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Professional Edge}. This edge must be tied to the story of your characters experiences during her life in the Last War.</li>\n<li>Use any leftover Hindrance points to take @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Setting Edges} if you like.</li>\n<li>Each @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} costs 2 Hindrance points.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Gear]{Gear}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Purchase up to 300 galifars (gp) worth of equipment.</li>\n</ul>\n<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7}}}
{"_id":"wl2uXpMiroMYZIiI","name":"Fixed Glory Awards","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Fixed Glory Awards</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Fixed Glory awards cover lesser deeds not played out (such as events during long periods of downtime), killing smaller number of foes during an adventure (they do slowly add up over time), or rewards for which there are many witnesses (battles or rescues). These are in addition to any Glory gained above.</p>\n<p>GM’s are encouraged to devise their own modifiers for things like concluding peace treaties or founding new mercantile routes that benefit a large population. Although notable deeds, the rewards for these types of endeavor should not be overly high—few people will remember who signed a peace treaty, but you can bet they’ll recall a hero who risked his life to venture into the heavily guarded camp of the enemy commander and kill him in an epic duel.</p>\n<h2>ACHIEVE RANK</h2>\n<p>Even without performing major heroic deeds, a hero can become famous through his collective lesser deeds. Such rewards are typical of the examples above, especially the slaying of lesser foes.</p>\n<p>These are wrapped into a single +5 Glory bonus gained when a hero achieves a new Rank. It is possible, though rare, for a hero to reach Legendary status with no additional Glory—he has performed many deeds, but none stand out as truly heroic.</p>\n<h2>Mass Battles</h2>\n<p>War is a terrible thing and something sane men avoid, but it can also grow and break reputations.</p>\n<p>Use the table below whenever the characters are involved in a fight using the Mass Battle rules. Whereas skirmishes are commonplace, true mass battles remain rare events. Hence, all Glory modifiers are fixed.</p>\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Mass Battle Glory Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Reason</th>\n<td class=\"table-column-header\" style=\"width:20%\">Modifier</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Size</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smallest army had hundreds of troops</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smallest army had thousands of troops</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smallest army had more than 10,000 troops</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Enemy</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hated rival of your nation</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+/–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Undead Army</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+/–2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Victory</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enemy had less tokens or was equal</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>For each token the enemy had above yours</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Defeat</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enemy had more tokens or was equal</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>For each token less your enemy had</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Personal Heroics</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Two raises on Heroes in Mass Battles rolls</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Commander</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>You commanded the army</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">x2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Character Roll:</strong> Scoring a double raise is more than just a die result. It represents a major event within a battle, such as slaying an enemy commander or slaughtering so many foes a battalion breaks.</p>\n<p>However, the modifier only applies if the number of enemy tokens was less than or equal to your army’s tokens at the time (slaying an enemy commander when you have a +3 bonus is nowhere near as heroic as when you have a –3 penalty.</p>\n<p><strong>Commander: </strong>A hero who commands an army gains greater Glory than his troops for victory, but also suffers more ignominy if he loses the field. Take the final Glory modifier and double it to see what the hero earned.</p>\n<p><strong>Defeat:</strong> Defeat is never easy to live with, but the ignominy is far worse if you outnumbered your foe. For each token you outnumbered your enemy at the start of a battle you suffer a –3 penalty.</p>\n<p><strong>Enemy Forces: </strong>Certain races are more despised than others. To qualify for the bonus, the specific enemy must account for more than 75% of the enemy army’s troop strength.</p>\n<p>Add the modifier if the heroes won, and subtract it if they lost (a defeat by a hated foe usually means the enemy will grow more confident and thus pose a greater danger in the future).</p>\n<p><strong>Size: </strong>Huge armies are rare in Khorvaire now the Last War is over, and thus while any battle earns Glory, the more participants there are the greater the tale told.</p>\n<p><strong>Victory: </strong>Everybody loves a winner. The greater the size of the enemy army, the more reward is earned. For each token your enemy’s army was larger than yours when battle commenced, the hero earns a +2 Glory bonus.</p>\n<h2>RESCUE</h2>\n<p>Even if the heroes’ tale of how they killed a hundred orcs doesn’t earn them any immediate Glory, having prisoners recount the tale of their rescue quickly causes word to spread.</p>\n<p>Important NPCs must be famous, powerful, and named. A merchant, wizard, priest, minor noble, or similar is worth +1 Glory. Saving a count or a skilled spellcaster is worth +3. Rescuing a prince, king, or truly powerful spellcaster gains the hero +5 Glory.</p>\n<p>For groups of lesser NPCs, rescuing ten or so is worth +1 Glory, a few tens +2, and a hundred or more +3. Saving a lone villager from an orc tribe is brave, but not enough to be retold by skalds.</p>\n<p>Rescue doesn’t have to mean entering a prison and breaking captives out. Liberating a village beset by frostreavers, for instance, counts as a rescue. If the rescue involves a Mass Battle rather than tabletop action, the party is deserving of the Mass Battle rewards as well.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Additional Glory Articles</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Variable Glorious Deeds]{Variable Glorious Deeds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fixed Glory Awards]{Fixed Glory Awards}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory Benefits]{Glory Benefits}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Losing Glory]{Losing Glory}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_lfqse89fhyg","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"wqqU4hNbMPWxGLno","name":"Bard/Skald","content":"<p>Bards and skalds usually don’t end up as wandering minstrels or street performers. Instead, some bards use their magical abilities to unearth ancient lore, while others use their interpersonal skills and song music to advance their careers as spies, ambassadors, diplomats, and chroniclers. As such, bards and skalds find employ as adventurers, as well as in governments and among the mercantile houses.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Taunt, Traditions</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Arcane Background (Song Magic), Attractive, Very Attractive, Charismatic, Fame, Famous, Linguist, Luck, Great Luck</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Any Leadership edges</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Acrobat, Entertainer, Femme Fatale/Ladykiller, Honey Tongue, Jack-of-all-Trades, Master Storyteller, Legendary Storyteller, Skald</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Bolser, Command Bond, Connections, Humiliate, Rabble-Rouse, Reliable, Streetwise, Work the Room, Work the Crowd <strong> </strong></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.V9GkKOtKpcThuSbb"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"xATNEaRpoy6q5ltP","name":"Cantrips","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Cantrips</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><img class=\"right table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/changeling-artificer.webp\" width=\"285\" height=\"500\" /></p>\n<p>A mage sets a broom to sweeping his floor. A priest lights a candle with the grace of her god. A bard tells an animated story in the night air, illuminated with the dancing cinders of a campfire. Such minor orisons (prayers) or lesser magicks are collectively called “cantrips.”</p>\n<p>In Savage Eberron, any character with an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Background} can cast cantrips.</p>\n<h2>ACTIVATION</h2>\n<p>A character may cast a cantrip by making an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill} roll. This is an action, and the effect must be based on one of the character’s existing powers. A sorcerer could use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> with a fire @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trapping} to light a campfire, for example. A druid could use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> to make vines dance to entertain a group of children. A wizard can use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound}</em> to ring a bell calling a servant to his study.</p>\n<p>Success means the desired effect occurs. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise} has an additional narrative impact of some kind—the candle glows brightly, the vines dance in perfect synchronicity, or the bell rings loud and pure.</p>\n<p>Failure causes the spell to fail without effect. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} causes the spell to backfire, which requires the caster to lose 1 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Point} (or suffer @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if the caster has no @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Points}). @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} also causes an embarrassment or minor mishap of some sort—an animated broom carelessly knocks a jar of ink onto the floor, a conjured flame lights a book on fire, or the power makes an embarrassing sound or smell.</p>\n<p>A successfully cast cantrip’s Duration is the same as the power it’s based on and may be maintained by spending @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Points} as usual.</p>\n<p>The DM has the final say on what a cantrip can do, but the effect must not replace a power or cause damage (at least directly). It can be used to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Test]{Test} or @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Support]{Support}, or grant a +1 bonus on a subsequent roll in the same encounter. For example, if the bard uses a cantrip to impress the children of Sharn, the DM might give him +1 to a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll later on if he talks to their parents or someone else who witnessed the kindness.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Magic and Powers</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Activation]{Activation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cantrips]{Cantrips}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{Schools of Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3> </h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0re3y8nenvi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.6SGCG8rZNklN3U6w"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":9},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"xRerrACw8WhWwoSS","name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","content":"","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_lfqse89fhyg","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000","name":"Setting Rules","children":["7vlY8JDlvPt6Lju1","wl2uXpMiroMYZIiI","vN3rOFTvBYis1Ybj","RdNbmZbTmR89KI0m","GframHMiA57wfqbr","1EDKN7kS6pIry1y7"],"folderPath":["temp_5n9ndtjortv","temp_s3sjll7e4a"]}}}
{"_id":"xeDF5hVR3YYg3qD0","name":"Halfling","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Halfling</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The halflings of Eberron originate from eastern Khorvaire, and many nomadic tribes of halflings still travel the Talenta Plains. The appearance of dragonmarks among the halflings spurred their slow migration across Khorvaire, spreading their services of healing and hospitality along with the migration of the earliest humans across the continent. Now they are found in every part of Khorvaire, putting their distinctive talents to use. </p>\n<h3>Talenta Halflings</h3>\n<p>The halflings who migrated across Khorvaire in the company of humans ended up looking very human in dress, manners, and customs. Their cousins who remain in the Talenta Plains could hardly appear more different. In their homeland, halflings are nomads who ride domesticated dinosaurs across the wide plains. Those few Talenta halflings who journey across Khorvaire are visibly out of place, both attracting curious stares and expressing plenty of curiosity of their own about the strange ways of Khorvaire's cities and towns.</p>\n<p>As you make a Talenta halfling character, give some thought to why your character left the open plains. Perhaps you served as a mercenary scout in the Last War, and you've remained with the comrades you met in the conflict. Maybe your tribe was wiped out by a foreign enemy, spurring you to travel the wider world in search of information and revenge. You might be guided by the spirits, who send you whispers and visions that lead you on your adventures. You could be an official envoy of your tribe seeking allies in the world, or simply sent to learn more about the lands beyond the plains.</p>\n<p>Also, consider your relationship to the dinosaurs that play a central role in the life of the Talenta halfiings. You might flavor your spells and class features as dinosaur-related: you could have a clawfoot companion, take on a fastieth form, name your combat styles and maneuvers after dinosaur attacks, or take inspiration from a glidewing (pteranodon) totem spirit. Or you could simply wear a dinosaur mask (as many Talenta halflings do), adorn yourself with claws and teeth from past dinosaur companions, or adopt dinosaur—like mannerisms. Wherever you travel, your connection to the dinosaurs ofyour home remains strong.</p>\n<p>Finally, it can be helpful to decide on a couple of behavioral quirks that reflect your culture. The Halfling Quirks table can provide some inspiration. </p>\n<h3>Halflings of the Five Nations</h3>\n<p>Quick and charming, many halflings put their natural talents to use as bards, barristers, merchants, and politicians throughout Khorvaire. Of course, these same talents prove equally useful for burglars, grifters, and other criminals.</p>\n<p>Of particular note is the halfling-run criminal enterprise of the Boromar Clan, the most powerful crime syndicate in Breland. The Boromars are based in Sham, but their influence reaches across the nation and even to the distant city of Stormreach. If you decide to play a halfling rogue, or a character with a criminal or charlatan background, consider (with your DM) whether you have a connection to the Boromar Clan. You could be a freelance operative who occasionally gets jobs from a Boromar underboss. You might have a cousin in the syndicate, who occasionally pulls you in to criminal affairs. Or you could even be the reluctant heir of a Boromar leader; perhaps you've gone on the run rather than take your appointed place in the criminal empire, but your past may yet catch up with you. You could also be the point ofcontact who has made the Boromar Clan your party's group patron.</p>\n<h3>Halflings and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>Two dragonmarks appear among the halflings of Khorvaire, the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Healing]{Mark of Healing}</em> in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Jorasco]{House Jorasco} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Ghallanda]{House Ghallanda's} <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Hospitality]{Mark of Hospitality}</em>. Both marks are ancient, first manifesting among the halflings about the same time that the elves of Aerenal received their first marks—centuries before the arrival of humans on Khorvaire. Sometimes halflings of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Ghallanda]{House Ghallanda}  joke that their mark prepared them for the arrival of humans by allowing them to make their new guests comfortable in Khorvaire. There's actually some truth in the humor: the services provided by both halfling houses helped enable the spread of humanity across the continent.</p>\n<p>With its powers related to food and shelter, the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Hospitality]{Mark of Hospitality}</em> was a boon to the early halfling nomads, but now it allows @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Ghallanda]{House Ghallanda} to run the best inns, hostels, and taverns in the land. Similarly, the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Healing]{Mark of Healing}</em> has always been a boon to both nomads and settlers facing dangerous wilds, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Jorasco]{House Jorasco} still employs both magical and mundane healing techniques to tend to the well-being of patients across Khorvaire.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Athletic: </strong>Halflings are nimble beings. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}. This increases their maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Diminutive:</strong> Halfling's average only about four feet tall, reducing their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>Fearless:</strong> Halflings have a natural happy and optimistic disposition that makes them naturally fearless. They start with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brave]{Brave} Edge.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Halflings from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Talenata Plains]{Talenata Plains} may start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Halfling} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong>Lucky: </strong>Halflings have a knack for surviving. They gain the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Luck]{Luck} Edge.</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced Pace:</strong> Halflings have short legs compared to human-sized races. Decrease their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} by 1 and their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running die} one die type.</li>\n<li><strong>Stealthy: </strong>Halflings are natural quiet and stealthy creatures. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth}. This increases their maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/halfling.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/halfling.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.HFDSzKgJIDSLuYy7"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"xirPwt6MtSTuoGxd","name":"Half-giant","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Half-giant</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Coming from either Sarlona or Xen’drik, they are now a true-breeding stock from the ancient Titans of Xen’drik. Half-giants, for the most part, retain human sensibilities. They are curious, interested in cooperation and communication, and have a general tendency toward kindness. (Half-Giants are from Sarlona and Xen’drik, talk to your DM if you want to play this race.)</p>\n<p>Perhaps the most baffling of all the races on the continent, the nomadic half-giants of Sarlona are descendants of ancient giant explorers from Xen'drik. Some say the half-giants are degenerate offspring of the Xen'drik titans, while others contend they have a mixed human ancestry.</p>\n<p>What can be said is that the true-breeding half-giants are racially inclined toward psionic ability, and this racial trait binds them into tight-knit but individually isolated bands. Half-giants refer to their groups as families, rather than tribes or clans, although few members of a family are actually blood-related. In fact, many families adopt individuals of other races, particularly psionic ones such as elans, dromites, duergar, and maenads.</p>\n<h3>Half-Giant Lands</h3>\n<p>Half-giant families wander endlessly all over Sarlona, although they rarely stray into Riedran territory. There, they are often \"assimilated\"—a process beginning as slavery. What is remarkable is the degree to which they tend to coexist peaceably with denizens of all other regions. In Tashana, where families are known collectively as the Icebinders, half-giants have a long tradition of trade and cooperation with the shifter and human tribes. The Sandstrider families of Syrkarn keep more to themselves, with occasional but minimal conflict with the humans and eneko of the region. In Adar, a handful of half-giant families called the pathadrik wander among the settlements and monasteries.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Cumbersome]{Cumbersome}: </strong>Half-giants aren't the most dextrous of creatures. They suffer a −1 penalty to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Fire Acclimated]{Fire Acclimated}:</strong> Half-giants are accustomed to enduring high temperatures. They gain a +4 bonus to resist the effects of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Heat]{heat} and fire. Damage from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Heat]{heat} and fire is also reduced by 4.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Natural Brute]{Natural Brute}:</strong> Half-giants have natural core strength and fitness over coordination and flexibility. They treat @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} as linked to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} instead of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} for purposes of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Advancement}. The character may also resist Athletics @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Test]{Tests} with Strength if she chooses. Finally, half-giants increase the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Short Range} of any thrown item by +1. Double that for the adjusted @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Medium Range}, and double again for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Long Range}. If a thrown item’s Range is 3/6/12, for example, a half-giant's @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Range} is 4/8/16.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Outsider (Eneko)]{Outsider (Minor)}:</strong> Most other races are put off by half-giants due to their abnormally large size. In fact, many are at first taken for young (if strangely well-groomed) hill giants. They have −2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} as other races tend to distrust them.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} +1:</strong> Half-giants are much larger than humans, standing about 6 ½ − 8 feet tall, increasing thier @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Stomp]{Stomp}:</strong> With a forceful stomp of their foot, half-giants can create a wave of trembling earth. With a successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll, targets caught within a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{Cone Template} originating from the half-giant’s step are knocked @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Prone]{Prone}; with a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise}, they are also @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Shaken}.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/half-giant.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/half-giant.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.vXetYPQjtecEgRPV"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"xnM0pGSbPLv4BpAC","name":"Fortification","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Armor Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Fortified armor is more likely to turn away a lethal blow. The wearer gains a free reroll on @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soak rolls}.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 2</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 5,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost trait}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"yIU3whNNgCXwDnJb","name":"Schools of Magic","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Schools of Magic</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><img class=\"right table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/wizard-at-study.webp\" width=\"265\" height=\"500\" /></p>\n<p>On Eberron, spells are categorized based on the effects generated by the power. These specialized groups are called schools. Any power not tied to a school of magic is considered to be a universal spell, such as <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wish]{wish}</em>. There are eight schools of magic: Abjuration, Conjuration, Divination, Enchantment, Evocation, Illusion, Necromancy, and Transmutation.</p>\n<p>A spell is always considered to be from its school, no matter where it comes from. <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost Trait}</em>, for example, is a Transmutation power, whether its cast from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Cleric)]{Arcane Background (Cleric)} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Sorcerer)]{Arcane Background (Sorcerer)}. The GM may decide, however, that a caster's specific trappings move the power into a different school for that caster (so a GM might rule that, while a typical barrier belongs to the conjuration school, a purely magical barrier might be an evocation spell instead).</p>\n<p>Knowing the schools of magic and their effects can be instrumental in identifying magical traps, weapons, items, or auras surrounding an opponent.</p>\n<p>Here are the various schools and the powers that belong to each. Note: these lists do not affect which powers an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Background} has access to. These lists simply identify which powers are associated to each particular school and the general focus of the school of magic.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Abjuration:</strong> The abjurer uses magic against itself, specializing in defensive magic.</li>\n<li><strong>Conjuration:</strong> Conjurers focus on spells to summon magical servants or bend reality to their will.</li>\n<li><strong>Divination:</strong> Diviners are masters of remote viewing and prophesies; they use their spells to explore the world.</li>\n<li><strong>Enchantment: </strong>The enchanter uses magic to manipulate the minds and perceptions of opponents.</li>\n<li><strong>Evocation: </strong>Evokers revel in the raw power of magic; they use spells to create and destroy with equal ease.</li>\n<li><strong>Illusion: </strong>Illusionists use magic to produce confounding sights, sounds and even smells to baffle and vex their opponents.</li>\n<li><strong>Necromancy: </strong>The dread necromancer commands undead and uses the foul power of unlife against enemies.</li>\n<li><strong>Transmutation: </strong>Transmuters use magic to change themselves and the world around them.</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-links-title\">Magic and Powers</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Activation]{Activation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cantrips]{Cantrips}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{Schools of Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3> </h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"cf":{"id":"temp_0re3y8nenvi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"yoUFXQcdUme8zOYF","name":"Dragonscale","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Dragonscale</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Armorers can fashion their products with the scales of dragons when such wonders become available. The age of the dragon determines the bonus for dragonscalee items (+1 to +4, GM’s call). The armor isn't considered metal, and provides @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} for attacks the dragon was immune to. For example blue dragonscale gives resistance to electricity. Dragonscale costs 100 times its armor bonus.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_ebw221m1i2","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/2.2. Materials and Craftsmanship","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"zDplrIRoqRkzZOx1","name":"Speed","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h3>Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>If a melee weapon, the user gains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy} Edge. A ranged weapon increases its @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Rate of Fire]{Rate of Fire} by 1, or reduces its @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Reload]{Reload} time by one action. User’s choice for weapons that can be used either way.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 3</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 16,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Speed}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_d6wak2736pv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/6.1. Enchantments","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
